    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-03T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-03T16:00:00-05:00" n="844"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d844">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 351.622a/53</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-03T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2968. Your 3745, April 13, 2 p. m.<note n="1" xml:id="d844fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_636">p. 636</ref>.</note>
                    Reply to Foreign Office that American-Hawaiian Steamship Company, owners of the
                        <hi rend="italic">Missourian</hi>, state that master of this vessel, just
                    previous to sailing from St. Nazaire, France, on June 16, found a German
                    stowaway on board who was sent ashore, and that on the morning after sailing,
                    another German stowaway was discovered whom on June 20 he turned over to the
                    steamer <hi rend="italic">Principello</hi>, bound back to St. Nazaire. As
                    obviously a stowaway is allowed to remain on board at the sufferance of the
                    captain, it is not perceived upon what ground this Government could reprimand
                    the captain for his action in turning the German stowaway over to a British ship
                    for transportation back to port, nor in the circumstances does this Government
                    believe that it should take such steps to require the surrender of the German as
                    have been taken in the case of the S. S. <hi rend="italic">China</hi> and other
                    cases in which Germans were seized from American vessels on the high seas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
